title: For Sale:  Steyr GB 9mm  Rare collectors gun Will Trade
postcontent:
I have a Steyr GB chambered in 9mm to sell...

These are pretty rare guns and have an interesting history...

They had a development time of nearly 20 years, and only about 15K were produced for worldwide sale.
They operate on a "Gas Brake" design similar to the H&K P7 and it has a fixed barrel
it has nearly no recoil and a very light recoil spring.
This gun is known to be super accurate and it has a "cult like" following

5 years ago they were easy to find... now not so much... when the magazines come up for sale people pay between $200-$250.00 just to score and extra.

This gun is in spectacular "safe queen" condition and comes with two magazines... the serial number is 14,1xx putting it in the last 900 guns produced according to my research that would be around 1988

Made in Austria... this is a serial numbers matching gun with all proper proof marks.

This gun was originally designed and built for the military and as such this is a Mil Spec gun with a chrome barrel that has  Polygonal Rifling 

The grips show no wear at all. and there are no real flaws in the finish
A very slight amount of holster wear at the nose, and the de-cocking lever has a shiny spot.

Asking $875.00 OBO for the complete package with two 18 round magazines and a plastic storage box.

Will Trade for a Winchester Model 70 in 300 Win Mag with a wood stock

I accept credit cards... You have to have the card in person to "swipe" and of course the card must match your ID

I will be doing a bill of sale so please have a valid VA drivers license or Military ID

shoot me a message if you want anymore pictures.

The hives are kept in my neighbor/partner's backyard, so the bees are gathering a really nice variety nectar from plants such as beans, golden rod, cotton, dandelion, maple, raspberry, blackberry, as well as other natural, yard, and garden/agriculture flora in the Hazel Green area. Most of the honey is jarred in quarts, but I do have a few pints and 1 lb squeeze bottles. Quarts are $12, pints are $7, and 1 lb squeeze bottles are $5. If you buy enough(at least 5 quarts), I will gladly give you a small discount. Email through Armslist if interested. I live in Hazel Green and work in Huntsville, so I can meet you anywhere in between after work. Or you can come pick it up at my house, so you can verify the location of the hives and that this is pure local honey.

title: For Sale:  Gun Storage Boxes/Crates
postcontent:
I am selling four (4) gun storage crates that I built a few years ago. I based the design on a smaller military crate I had at the time. Here are the highlights of the construction:

-I sealed the interior seams with silicone caulk. I then polyurethaned the interior and exterior (3 coats). I added a foam strip to the top rail for a seal.
-Each crate has two sets of vertical rails for inserts. Each set of inserts holds five (5) long guns; each crate holds fifteen (15) long guns.
-The lids are secured/anchored with several lag bolts with washers.
-Each crate has a small desiccant cartridge (from Cabelas) for moisture control. These cartridges can be removed and "reset" by baking them in an oven for a few hours.
-Each crate has a heavy-duty metal handles on both sides

Here are the dimensions of the crates:

Short Crate (3 of them)

title: For Sale/Trade:  US Army Issue Colt M1901 Army Double Action Revolver
postcontent:
The Colt 1901 was a slightly modified version of the Colt 1892 "New Army and Navy" revolver.
The first model in this early DA revolver was the Model 1889 "New Navy" which went through several modifications, including the Models 1892, 1994, 1896, 1901, and finally the 1903.

These were the first swing-out cylinder double action revolvers ever made, and Colt revolutionized revolvers with the new design. S&W wouldn't get their first swing-out DA on the market until 1896.

These pistols were forerunners of all the Colt DA revolvers that followed, and the basic design was made up until the Colt Python was discontinued in 2004.  These early series guns were discontinued in 1907, with about 291,000 produced for all models.

The US Army and Navy bought large quantities of these revolvers in the now obsolete .38 Long Colt cartridge.  It was this design Colt and the .38 Long cartridge that failed in the Philippines and led to the adoption of the Model 1911 .45 Automatic.

This is a genuine US Army issue M1901 US military model, as evidenced by the  markings on the butt, grips and frame.   The grips are the original smooth walnut grip with the inspector stamp of RAC on each side.  RAC were the initials of Rinaldo A. Carr the civilian government employed sub-inspector at Colt, between 1890 to 1903. The frame is also stamped RAC and L.E.B.  The initials L .E.B. belonging to one Leroy E. Briggs, an Army Captain that inspected revolvers rebuilt and refurbished at Remington's Bridgeport plant between 1898 to 1917.  

The bottom of the butt is perfectly marked "U.S.ARMY MODEL 1901." and "No 157271."  The serial number indicates it was manufactured and delivered to the US Army in 1901.   The round barrel is clearly marked with two line Colt address and patent dates ending with  “March 5, 95”. The barrel and frame have 90% original blue finish with some thinning and patina to the backstrap and front strap. Dull blue finish remains on the rear surfaces of the hammer with about 50% remaining on the trigger. Action works perfectly and appears to be still in time. The walnut grips are smooth and in very good condition, although one front corner is missing a small chip.  A swivel lanyard strap is on the butt of the pistol. Overall condition is very good. Will ship to your FFL.   This gun is priced to sell at the low end of the 2011 gun values guide and often sell for considerably larger sums.  Offers and trades of like value considered.

It is estimated that less than 400 total of this model were ever imported into the US prior to the ban, which disallowed several features, one of them being the folding stock. These (Norinco 56S-2) rifles were all manufactured by the Norinco which was the commercial side of the Chinese State Arms factory which produced the very best AK rifles. Made with threaded muzzle, and with the bayonet lug like the milled "Legend" versions. A rare chance to get a premium, highly collectible, pre-ban AK-47.    REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Enfield/Webley No. 2 Mk 1 - .38S&W +60 rounds factory ammo+holster
postcontent:
This revolver was developed at the Royal Small Arms Factory in Enfield in 1926 - 1927. The design is based on scaled down Webley Mark 6 "break-top" frame, with cylinder chambered for 6 .38/200 rounds. The hammer/trigger group was redesigned, with manual hammer safety lock added, and with separate cylinder lock. This revolver was adopted for British Military service in 1932 as Enfield revolver, .38 caliber, No.2 Mark 1. After 1938, almost all No.2 Mk1s were converted into No.2 Mark 1 configuration.

Enfield No.2 Mark 1 were developed in the late 1930s for British Tank Corps. The spurless DAO hammers were required by Tank Corps command to avoid snagging the hammers on tank internals.

Enfield No.2 Mark 1 appeared in the 1942 as a simplified, wartime design. These guns were similar to No.2 Mark 1, but without the hammer stop. After 1945, all those revolvers were recalled and converted into No.2 Mark 1.

I am asking $450 FTF OBO for this revolver and I am including 60 rounds of factory loaded ammunition for the gun. I am also including a leather holster that was with the gun when it was given to me. Lockup and timing is great. 

I will travel almost anywhere in the Seattle/Tacoma area - maybe farther for serious offers.
I am willing to ship to an FFL - you pay shipping. 

If $450 doesn't work, make me a reasonable offer.

The MUR was developed to give the customer a MilSpec correct upper receiver with a thicker wall, making the MUR upper receiver a stronger platform. This more rigid upper receiver will increase accuracy and reliability, while extending the life of the interfacing components, such as the bolt carrier group and barrel assembly.

The MUR comes in two models: one with a Bolt-Assist/Shell-Deflector and the second with a Shell Deflector only. All MURs feature a MilStd-1913 scope mounting rail and come equipped with an Ejection-Port, Dust Cover Door.
